Project Overview
Automated tilt adjustment for 6x 420W solar panels (1722mm x 1134mm) mounted on a 1800mm high timber fence. The system uses a NEMA17-driven linear actuator to adjust panel tilt between 10° and 65° to optimise yield and manage wind loads in a high-exposure environment.
1. Geometry & Linkage (Fixed Dimensions)
Hinge Pivot (Origin): Located at the back-top edge of the 100x50mm horizontal fence rail.
Panel Mount Point (
): 740mm from the hinge pivot, located on the vertical centreline of the frame uprights.
Swing Arm Length (
): 650mm (Rigid arm connecting the slider to the panel mount).
Slider Rail (
): M8 Threaded Rod mounted vertically to the fence post, starting below the hinge.
Travel Range: To achieve 10° to 60° tilt:
10° Position: Slider is 91.6mm from the hinge.
60° Position: Slider is 261.4mm from the hinge.
Total Travel Required: ~170mm (within the 600mm rod length).
2. Frame Construction
Uprights: 2x 1722mm timber boards (75x30mm) bolted to the solar panel rear.
Cross Members: 3x 1134mm boards. Hinge member (CM2) is 920mm from the frame bottom.
Hinge Mounting: Butt hinges connect the top face of the rail to the sun-side face of CM2. The panel hangs vertically (0°) when flush against the fence.
3. Drive System (Captive Rod Design)
Motor: NEMA17 High Torque (45Ncm+ / 17HS19-2004S).
Drive Rod: 600mm M8 Stainless Threaded Rod (replaces M12 for better NEMA17 compatibility).
Guide Rod: Parallel M6 threaded rod to prevent slider rotation.
Slider Block: 3D-printed (ASA/PETG) housing an M8 brass nut, 7mm guide hole, and mounting point for the 650mm swing arm.
Thrust Management: 2x 608-2RS bearings (common 8mm skate bearings) in printed mounts to isolate the motor from the weight of the panel.
4. Mechanical Specs & Environment
Location: Todmorden, UK (High wind/moisture).
Material: All 3D prints in ASA or PETG (5+ walls, 40% gyroid infill). All rods/fasteners A2 Stainless Steel.
Safety: "Storm Mode" (Return to 10°/Vertical) triggered via software for high wind speeds.
Resolution: 1.25mm pitch (Standard M8) provides extremely fine angular control and high mechanical advantage.
Mechanical Warning: Motor Torque vs. Threaded Rod Choice
You initially mentioned an M12 rod, but your locked dimensions now specify an M8 rod.
The M8 advantage: Standard M8 has a 1.25mm pitch. This is 
 more powerful than an 8mm lead (T8) screw.
Result: With an M8 rod, your NEMA17 will handle the 2kg–5kg load with ease, even at the difficult 10° starting position, as the "inclined plane" of the thread is much shallower.